WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:00.084 --> 00:00:04.463
[DJ] Let's give it up one more time
for the birthday girl Elle Woods!

2
00:00:04.547 --> 00:00:06.340
Previously on Elle...

3
00:00:06.424 --> 00:00:07.717
[guests cheering]

4
00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:10.761
We have something important
we want to talk to you about.

5
00:00:10.845 --> 00:00:11.846
Elle. we're moving to Seattle.

6
00:00:11.929 --> 00:00:14.390
[crying]

7
00:00:14.473 --> 00:00:16.350
[Elle] I know it's scary.
but this is just gonna be

8
00:00:16.434 --> 00:00:18.728
our new home for a little while.

9
00:00:19.228 --> 00:00:21.355
[indistinct chatter]

10
00:00:21.439 --> 00:00:22.398
I'm Elle.

11
00:00:22.481 --> 00:00:23.691
Did someone put you up to this?

12
00:00:24.442 --> 00:00:26.777
[clanging]

13
00:00:26.861 --> 00:00:28.237
-[groans]
-[gasps] Oh!

14
00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:29.530
-Oh.
-Oh. [stammers]

15
00:00:29.613 --> 00:00:30.698
Sorry. Are you okay?

16
00:00:31.282 --> 00:00:32.283
Yeah.

17
00:00:32.366 --> 00:00:33.784
Seattle isn't a costume.

18
00:00:33.868 --> 00:00:35.995
and pink isn't a personality.

19
00:00:36.078 --> 00:00:36.954
Did you make any friends?

20
00:00:37.037 --> 00:00:38.789
[Elle] Does the school secretary count?

21
00:00:38.873 --> 00:00:40.124
[Madison] It's a great jumping-off point.

22
00:00:40.207 --> 00:00:43.252
[Elle] I don't feel like I really speak
the same language as anyone here.

23
00:00:43.335 --> 00:00:44.462
Get fluent in Seattle.

24
00:00:45.212 --> 00:00:46.756
[Elle] This is money going directly

25
00:00:46.839 --> 00:00:51.343
into Donna's pocket and into the pocket
of dozens of other Donnas at this school.

26
00:00:51.427 --> 00:00:52.678
-Thirty.
-[gasping. cheering]

27
00:00:52.762 --> 00:00:54.513
[students] Donna! Donna!

28
00:00:54.597 --> 00:00:56.390
-Donna!
-[Kimberly] Oh. you didn't hear?

29
00:00:56.474 --> 00:00:58.476
Your little stunt yesterday
got Donna fired.

30
00:01:03.773 --> 00:01:06.901
[♪ R.E.M. plays "Shiny Happy People"]

31
00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:09.904
♪ Whoa. here we go ♪

32
00:01:09.987 --> 00:01:13.532
[singer vocalizing]

33
00:01:13.616 --> 00:01:17.036
♪ Shiny. happy people holding hands ♪

34
00:01:17.119 --> 00:01:20.206
-♪ Shiny. happy people ♪
-Hi. Elle.

35
00:01:20.289 --> 00:01:21.540
♪ holding hands ♪

36
00:01:21.624 --> 00:01:22.958
♪ Shiny. happy...

37
00:01:23.042 --> 00:01:24.752
Oh. I love your boots. Elle.

38
00:01:24.835 --> 00:01:26.128
Thanks. They're waterproof.

39
00:01:26.212 --> 00:01:28.214
Not that we have to worry about that here.

40
00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:31.050
[Amber] Oh. my God. Elle.

41
00:01:31.133 --> 00:01:33.219
You look so tan.

42
00:01:33.302 --> 00:01:35.221
It is L.A. after all.

43
00:01:36.263 --> 00:01:37.515
[girl] Hi. Elle!

44
00:01:38.516 --> 00:01:40.309
[clears throat]

45
00:01:40.392 --> 00:01:41.644
Hot Josh.

46
00:01:41.727 --> 00:01:43.604
You're looking very...

47
00:01:43.687 --> 00:01:44.688
Hot?

48
00:01:44.772 --> 00:01:45.773
Precisely.

49
00:01:45.856 --> 00:01:47.274
There she is.

50
00:01:47.358 --> 00:01:51.070
Oh. Elle. you make high school
look so easy.

51
00:01:51.153 --> 00:01:54.240
[students shouting "Elle!"]

52
00:01:54.323 --> 00:01:56.242
[Donna] Elle Woods!

53
00:01:56.325 --> 00:02:00.412
[fading] ♪ Shiny. happy people
holding hands ♪♪

54
00:02:00.496 --> 00:02:02.498
[ominous music playing]

55
00:02:04.166 --> 00:02:05.167
Donna?

56
00:02:07.711 --> 00:02:08.754
What are you doing in Bel Air?

57
00:02:10.089 --> 00:02:11.757
-[panting]
-[rain falling]

58
00:02:11.841 --> 00:02:13.384
-Oh.
-[thunder rumbling]

59
00:02:14.385 --> 00:02:15.928
Seattle?

60
00:02:17.012 --> 00:02:19.515
[Bruiser whimpering]

61
00:02:21.308 --> 00:02:23.936
I wish we could wake up
from this nightmare. Bruiser.

62
00:02:24.687 --> 00:02:26.939
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

63
00:02:27.022 --> 00:02:28.440
[♪ Garbage sings
"I'm Only Happy When It Rains"]

64
00:02:28.524 --> 00:02:32.653
♪ I'm only happy when it's complicated ♪

65
00:02:32.736 --> 00:02:34.655
♪ And though I know you can't ♪

66
00:02:34.738 --> 00:02:36.657
♪ appreciate it ♪

67
00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:40.077
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

68
00:02:40.744 --> 00:02:42.705
♪ Pour your ♪

69
00:02:42.788 --> 00:02:44.707
-♪ misery down ♪
-♪ Pour your misery ♪

70
00:02:44.790 --> 00:02:48.711
-♪ Pour your misery down on me ♪
-♪ down. pour your misery ♪

71
00:02:48.794 --> 00:02:52.715
-♪ Pour your misery down ♪
-♪ down. pour ♪

72
00:02:52.798 --> 00:02:56.719
♪ You can keep me company as long as ♪

73
00:02:56.802 --> 00:02:58.762
♪ you don't care ♪

74
00:03:00.806 --> 00:03:04.101
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

75
00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:08.063
♪ You wanna hear about my new obsession? ♪

76
00:03:08.147 --> 00:03:10.065
♪ I'm riding high upon ♪

77
00:03:10.149 --> 00:03:12.526
♪ a deep depression ♪

78
00:03:12.610 --> 00:03:14.987
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

79
00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:18.574
♪ Pour some misery down on me ♪

80
00:03:18.657 --> 00:03:20.993
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

81
00:03:21.076 --> 00:03:24.038
♪ Pour some misery down on me ♪♪

82
00:03:24.121 --> 00:03:25.706
-[growls softly]
-[Wyatt] Don't you...

83
00:03:25.789 --> 00:03:26.832
No. No. no. no. no.

84
00:03:26.916 --> 00:03:28.876
-no. no. no. no. no. no.
-Wait. baby. wait!

85
00:03:28.959 --> 00:03:30.753
-And that would be
the third chair this week.
-[barks]

86
00:03:30.836 --> 00:03:32.296
I'll have to toss it with the others.

87
00:03:32.379 --> 00:03:34.048
I'm sorry. we're throwing out
our furniture?

88
00:03:34.131 --> 00:03:36.133
Our furniture that we rented?

89
00:03:36.216 --> 00:03:38.135
-Honey. you're. you're shaming him.
-[whimpering]

90
00:03:38.218 --> 00:03:42.514
If anything. Bruiser's given us
a perfect excuse to redecorate.

91
00:03:42.598 --> 00:03:44.099
[sighs]

92
00:03:44.183 --> 00:03:45.351
Didn't he. Daddy?

93
00:03:45.434 --> 00:03:47.728
-[barking]
-Grandfather? Where did we land with that?

94
00:03:47.811 --> 00:03:50.981
-I-I'm not sure. But thanks. buddy.
-Aw.

95
00:03:51.065 --> 00:03:54.109
If our little baby
won't tinkle outside in Seattle.

96
00:03:54.193 --> 00:03:57.863
I'll just have to bring L.A. to him
like I did for Mama Elle's room.

97
00:03:57.947 --> 00:04:00.699
I'm thinking real grass.

98
00:04:00.783 --> 00:04:02.701
doggy pool. heat lamp.

99
00:04:02.785 --> 00:04:05.287
I think they sell soil
at the farmers market co-op.

100
00:04:05.371 --> 00:04:06.747
How many of those words are made-up?

101
00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:09.166
[Wyatt] A co-op.
It's like a Bristol Farms under a tent.

102
00:04:09.249 --> 00:04:11.335
Dad. you're home.

103
00:04:11.418 --> 00:04:14.880
[gasps] People in Seattle
don't want nose jobs?

104
00:04:14.964 --> 00:04:17.466
Turns out. people in Seattle
like all kinds of noses.

105
00:04:17.549 --> 00:04:19.134
Even their own.

106
00:04:19.218 --> 00:04:20.719
-Wow.
-Things'll pick up

107
00:04:20.803 --> 00:04:22.680
once grunge runs its course.

108
00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:25.182
[Eva] You sleep okay. sweetie?

109
00:04:25.265 --> 00:04:27.226
You have a slight case of the Birkins.

110
00:04:27.309 --> 00:04:31.480
Are you still upset
about that secretary getting let go?

111
00:04:31.563 --> 00:04:32.982
Of course. It's awful.

112
00:04:33.065 --> 00:04:35.401
Donna was such a kind person.
She didn't deserve this.

113
00:04:35.484 --> 00:04:40.114
Well. wasn't she caught embezzling funds
and forging documents?

114
00:04:40.197 --> 00:04:42.116
I mean. Al Capone was arrested for less.

115
00:04:42.199 --> 00:04:43.784
But her heart was in the right place.

116
00:04:43.867 --> 00:04:45.369
[Wyatt] The court of public opinion
wanted to hang

117
00:04:45.452 --> 00:04:47.538
your old man not too long ago.

118
00:04:47.621 --> 00:04:49.581
If you want to throw her a bone.
I'd be happy to put a call in

119
00:04:49.665 --> 00:04:51.125
-to our crisis manager.
-The one

120
00:04:51.208 --> 00:04:53.836
that convinced you to move
to the city God and Gucci forgot?

121
00:04:53.919 --> 00:04:55.754
[hopeful music playing]

122
00:04:55.838 --> 00:04:58.757
-[school bell ringing]
-[indistinct chatter]

123
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

124
00:05:13.522 --> 00:05:15.190
Yeah. [chuckles]
Yeah. we'll be there.

125
00:05:15.274 --> 00:05:16.400
[chuckles]

126
00:05:17.651 --> 00:05:19.445
Good morning. Kimberly.

127
00:05:19.528 --> 00:05:20.821
Happy Monday. Pink Slip.

128
00:05:20.904 --> 00:05:22.322
Oh. this isn't a slip.

129
00:05:22.406 --> 00:05:23.907
It's more of an alpaca tweed.

130
00:05:23.991 --> 00:05:24.992
She doesn't get it.

131
00:05:25.075 --> 00:05:26.452
Of course she doesn't.

132
00:05:27.453 --> 00:05:28.662
Anyway.

133
00:05:28.746 --> 00:05:30.998
per Donna's unjust termination.

134
00:05:31.081 --> 00:05:34.543
I thought maybe we could rally the student
body and do something nice in her honor.

135
00:05:34.626 --> 00:05:37.838
For example. when the Oscars
snubbed Anjelica Huston

136
00:05:37.921 --> 00:05:39.214
for The Addams Family Values.

137
00:05:39.298 --> 00:05:41.675
my friends and I collected money
for a chimp sanctuary.

138
00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:43.969
I don't think she's kidding.

139
00:05:45.095 --> 00:05:48.223
Elle. I'm sure
Anjelica Huston loved knowing

140
00:05:48.307 --> 00:05:51.268
that you and your friends found a way
to make her awards season all about you.

141
00:05:51.351 --> 00:05:53.395
-Oh. [stammers]
-But wouldn't the best way

142
00:05:53.479 --> 00:05:56.940
to honor Donna have been
not getting her fired in the first place?

143
00:05:57.649 --> 00:05:59.234
[Katie] Basically. no one wants to be seen

144
00:05:59.318 --> 00:06:01.403
-with you.
-Yeah. she gets it. Katie.

145
00:06:01.487 --> 00:06:04.198
Anyway. I'm gonna go honor Donna
by being really bummed.

146
00:06:04.281 --> 00:06:08.535
and you can go do whatever you need to do
to make this all about you.

147
00:06:13.874 --> 00:06:16.752
[wistful music playing]

148
00:06:16.835 --> 00:06:18.420
[rain falling]

149
00:06:18.504 --> 00:06:20.047
[line ringing]

150
00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:23.467
[thunder rumbling]

151
00:06:23.550 --> 00:06:25.260
[Madison] Elle?
I just got your emergency page.

152
00:06:25.344 --> 00:06:26.845
One-eight-seven?

153
00:06:26.929 --> 00:06:29.598
Does that mean bad haircut.
or are you being held at gunpoint?

154
00:06:30.682 --> 00:06:32.810
I don't make everything about me. do I?

155
00:06:32.893 --> 00:06:34.686
Of course not.

156
00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:36.980
You're notoriously bad
at accepting a compliment.

157
00:06:37.064 --> 00:06:39.441
It's one of your most endearing qualities.

158
00:06:39.525 --> 00:06:40.609
Stop.

159
00:06:40.692 --> 00:06:42.027
Wait.

160
00:06:42.111 --> 00:06:43.403
why aren't you at school?

161
00:06:43.487 --> 00:06:45.364
Oh. there was an earthquake this morning.

162
00:06:45.447 --> 00:06:46.949
Oh. my God. You should've 187'd me.

163
00:06:47.032 --> 00:06:48.033
It wasn't bad.

164
00:06:48.117 --> 00:06:50.661
It just... It messed
with our collective chi.

165
00:06:52.037 --> 00:06:53.455
I miss earthquakes.

166
00:06:53.539 --> 00:06:55.541
My dad's new girlfriend
is using it as an excuse

167
00:06:55.624 --> 00:06:57.292
to have me chauffeur her around all day.

168
00:06:57.376 --> 00:06:58.836
So now I'm waiting

169
00:06:58.919 --> 00:07:01.088
outside the Polo Lounge
like some kind of...

170
00:07:02.089 --> 00:07:04.091
Pause.

171
00:07:04.174 --> 00:07:05.676
I just found a way to get you home.

172
00:07:07.344 --> 00:07:10.139
Cosmo's doing
a semester-long internship in L.A.

173
00:07:10.222 --> 00:07:11.348
Oh. my God.

174
00:07:11.431 --> 00:07:13.016
My parents would have to let me move back
for something like that.

175
00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:14.351
-[chuckles]
-I'd be a shoo-in

176
00:07:14.434 --> 00:07:16.270
-at CULA.
-You could live

177
00:07:16.353 --> 00:07:17.354
in our pool house.

178
00:07:17.437 --> 00:07:20.232
You know that singer that my dad thinks
is gonna be the next big thing?

179
00:07:20.315 --> 00:07:22.151
She just moved out. Christina...

180
00:07:22.234 --> 00:07:23.819
Aguachile or something.

181
00:07:23.902 --> 00:07:24.903
Okay. Tell me

182
00:07:24.987 --> 00:07:26.488
how to win immediately.

183
00:07:26.572 --> 00:07:28.448
Okay. I think you just need to choose
from a few

184
00:07:28.532 --> 00:07:30.742
of these essay prompts. Um...

185
00:07:30.826 --> 00:07:32.870
Mm. Oh. Here.

186
00:07:32.953 --> 00:07:36.165
"Cosmo girls get knocked down.
but they get up again.

187
00:07:36.248 --> 00:07:37.791
When things get bad.

188
00:07:37.875 --> 00:07:39.376
how would you stage your comeback?"

189
00:07:41.253 --> 00:07:43.005
How do you stage a comeback?

190
00:07:43.088 --> 00:07:44.089
I think

191
00:07:44.173 --> 00:07:45.674
you just have kids or go on SNL.

192
00:07:45.757 --> 00:07:49.094
But I'm a virgin.
and I can't wait until Saturday.

193
00:07:50.721 --> 00:07:52.472
I could write about Donna's comeback.

194
00:07:52.556 --> 00:07:53.932
I can help her get rehired.

195
00:07:54.016 --> 00:07:55.893
She really deserves a second chance here.

196
00:07:57.895 --> 00:07:59.479
Wait. but isn't that kind of hard?

197
00:07:59.563 --> 00:08:01.190
You're Elle Woods.

198
00:08:01.273 --> 00:08:04.568
I've seen you open six cans of Fanta
without breaking one acrylic nail.

199
00:08:05.235 --> 00:08:06.737
I did do that.

200
00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:10.490
[sighs] Okay. I can do this.

201
00:08:10.574 --> 00:08:13.285
I'll get Donna her job back.
crush this essay.

202
00:08:13.368 --> 00:08:15.287
and put Seattle in my rearview.

203
00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:17.080
Let's get you home. Elle.

204
00:08:17.164 --> 00:08:18.373
-[soft chatter]
-No.

205
00:08:18.457 --> 00:08:20.292
I miss CarpetMart being uncool.

206
00:08:20.375 --> 00:08:22.920
Once Layne Staley rolled through.
it was game over.

207
00:08:23.003 --> 00:08:24.880
I'm sorry. Liz.

208
00:08:24.963 --> 00:08:27.299
If I hear of anybody selling tickets.
I'll let you know.

209
00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:33.347
I'd ask you what CarpetMart is.
but I assume you're mad at me. too.

210
00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:35.015
I actually didn't even notice you.

211
00:08:35.098 --> 00:08:37.267
Which. I don't know. is that worse?

212
00:08:37.351 --> 00:08:39.603
Under normal circumstances. yes.

213
00:08:39.686 --> 00:08:42.898
But with everyone hating me
'cause of the whole Donna thing.

214
00:08:42.981 --> 00:08:44.691
invisibility is a welcome change.

215
00:08:44.775 --> 00:08:46.610
The Donna "thing"?

216
00:08:46.693 --> 00:08:48.195
Getting her fired.

217
00:08:48.278 --> 00:08:49.363
But worry not.

218
00:08:49.446 --> 00:08:51.990
This is just the origin story
of Donna's epic comeback.

219
00:08:52.074 --> 00:08:54.576
I have ideas to get Donna rehired.

220
00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:56.912
Not number three. She hates bowling.

221
00:08:56.995 --> 00:09:00.415
Weird that she hates fun
for the whole family. but good to know.

222
00:09:01.416 --> 00:09:03.919
And who is Judge Judy Sheindlin?

223
00:09:04.002 --> 00:09:08.006
[gasps] Only the most brilliant
family court judge in Manhattan.

224
00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:10.300
She just needs a better platform
to showcase her talents.

225
00:09:10.926 --> 00:09:13.262
-[gasps] But you're right.
-[school bell rings]

226
00:09:13.345 --> 00:09:15.097
She's probably busy.

227
00:09:15.180 --> 00:09:16.682
[door shuts]

228
00:09:16.765 --> 00:09:18.433
[Nichols] Okay. People. today

229
00:09:18.517 --> 00:09:21.645
we are talking mice and we're talking men.

230
00:09:21.728 --> 00:09:23.021
We are talking...

231
00:09:24.106 --> 00:09:26.108
...Of Mice and Men.

232
00:09:26.191 --> 00:09:28.235
[student] The book is boring.
Can we read something more...

233
00:09:28.318 --> 00:09:30.112
not boring?

234
00:09:30.195 --> 00:09:31.571
[Nichols] Well. this...

235
00:09:31.655 --> 00:09:35.033
"boring" book was deemed a critical part
of your junior year curriculum

236
00:09:35.117 --> 00:09:37.327
by the Washington State Board
of Education.

237
00:09:37.411 --> 00:09:40.122
So if you really have an issue with it.

238
00:09:40.205 --> 00:09:42.457
I don't know.
start a petition or something.

239
00:09:43.458 --> 00:09:45.210
That's perfect.

240
00:09:45.294 --> 00:09:46.295
Mr. Nichols.

241
00:09:47.838 --> 00:09:49.923
-You're brilliant.
-[light snickering]

242
00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:51.591
Thank you.

243
00:09:53.135 --> 00:09:54.136
Okay.

244
00:09:54.219 --> 00:09:55.387
Of Mice and Men.

245
00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.973
Yet another example
of why California sucks.

246
00:09:59.808 --> 00:10:01.435
You're supposed
to be learning things here.

247
00:10:01.518 --> 00:10:02.936
When did you have time to do this?

248
00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:04.604
Well. technically I didn't do it.

249
00:10:04.688 --> 00:10:07.149
I gave one of the cheerleaders
all my liquid black eyeliner

250
00:10:07.232 --> 00:10:09.276
to collect signatures from our classmates
because I needed

251
00:10:09.359 --> 00:10:11.361
a proxy as a result
of no one liking me here.

252
00:10:11.445 --> 00:10:14.948
Okay. And you think a few signatures
are gonna get Donna her job back?

253
00:10:15.032 --> 00:10:18.952
These 117 signatures
embody our unified voice.

254
00:10:19.036 --> 00:10:22.956
a testament to our unwavering resolve
that injustice will not be tolerated.

255
00:10:23.707 --> 00:10:26.126
Sure... Donna broke a few rules.

256
00:10:26.209 --> 00:10:28.295
But it was all in the interest
of helping people.

257
00:10:28.378 --> 00:10:29.880
She was caught stealing money.

258
00:10:29.963 --> 00:10:32.549
Well. she bought a starving kid lunch
with petty cash.

259
00:10:32.632 --> 00:10:34.509
Caleb i-is not starving.

260
00:10:34.593 --> 00:10:36.762
His parents are going through a divorce.

261
00:10:36.845 --> 00:10:40.432
and sometimes things like lunch money
get lost in the shuffle.

262
00:10:40.515 --> 00:10:42.059
Well. thank goodness for Donna. then.

263
00:10:43.518 --> 00:10:47.522
You recognize I'm an adult. right?

264
00:10:47.606 --> 00:10:49.441
Did your last school
have any sense of authority?

265
00:10:49.524 --> 00:10:51.860
-[chuckles]
-All sparkly clean.

266
00:10:51.943 --> 00:10:53.320
I left your car in your spot.

267
00:10:54.279 --> 00:10:56.615
And the detailing guy found this jacket
under your passenger seat.

268
00:10:56.698 --> 00:10:59.659
Ah. Uh. thank you. Ms. Martindale.

269
00:11:01.286 --> 00:11:05.165
Principal Anderson.
while I do love a bold citrus.

270
00:11:05.248 --> 00:11:09.169
I'm not sure orange suede maximizes
the potential of your complexion.

271
00:11:09.252 --> 00:11:10.212
It's my wife's.

272
00:11:10.295 --> 00:11:14.257
Oh. You mean that stone-cold fox
pretending to like sports?

273
00:11:14.341 --> 00:11:16.468
Not pretending.
Born and raised Mariners junkie.

274
00:11:16.551 --> 00:11:19.221
And flattery is not gonna get
Donna her job back. Get to class.

275
00:11:19.304 --> 00:11:20.680
Well. Principal Anderson.

276
00:11:20.764 --> 00:11:22.516
Donna deserves a second chance here.

277
00:11:22.599 --> 00:11:24.309
Even if I agreed with you. it's too late.

278
00:11:24.393 --> 00:11:26.645
She's working at Pike Place Market now.

279
00:11:27.479 --> 00:11:29.189
Donna already found a new job?

280
00:11:29.272 --> 00:11:31.108
She's not coming back. Elle.

281
00:11:31.691 --> 00:11:33.110
Get to class.

282
00:11:39.032 --> 00:11:41.034
[intriguing music playing]

283
00:11:42.119 --> 00:11:44.121
[indistinct chatter]

284
00:11:50.252 --> 00:11:52.963
[woman over P.A.] Half-off special
for shellfish at the fish counter.

285
00:11:53.046 --> 00:11:54.172
-[bell clangs]
-Order! Salmon!

286
00:11:54.256 --> 00:11:55.257
Hey-ya!

287
00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:57.801
[gasping. laughter]

288
00:11:58.969 --> 00:12:00.387
-[bell clangs]
-Hey-ya!

289
00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:01.805
-[woman] Whoo!
-[overlapping chatter]

290
00:12:01.888 --> 00:12:03.306
Donna?

291
00:12:03.807 --> 00:12:06.476
I know I'm probably the last person
you want to talk to

292
00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:09.813
and that you have easy access
to a boning knife.

293
00:12:09.896 --> 00:12:11.773
but I'm really. really sorry
you got fired.

294
00:12:12.983 --> 00:12:14.192
Aw.

295
00:12:14.276 --> 00:12:17.279
Thanks. Elle.
but there is nothing to be sorry about.

296
00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:19.281
-[bell clangs]
-Do I wish you hadn't shared

297
00:12:19.364 --> 00:12:22.576
my tricks of the trade
with the entire student body? Yes.

298
00:12:22.659 --> 00:12:25.662
But they are my tricks.
and I got to own 'em.

299
00:12:25.745 --> 00:12:27.664
This is exactly why I started a petition

300
00:12:27.747 --> 00:12:29.749
in your honor arguing you were a victim

301
00:12:29.833 --> 00:12:31.042
of injustice and deserve your job back.

302
00:12:31.126 --> 00:12:32.043
You started a petition?

303
00:12:32.127 --> 00:12:34.921
-Mm-hmm. 117 signatures strong.
-[bell clangs]

304
00:12:35.005 --> 00:12:37.340
But Principal Anderson
was aggressively unmoved.

305
00:12:37.424 --> 00:12:38.550
He's such a stickler.

306
00:12:39.634 --> 00:12:41.803
Elle. you shouldn't be trying
to fix this with him.

307
00:12:41.887 --> 00:12:43.013
[gasps] You're right.

308
00:12:43.096 --> 00:12:45.849
We need to go higher.
like the school superintendent.

309
00:12:46.725 --> 00:12:49.352
I have a Jackie O suit skirt
I have been dying to mobilize.

310
00:12:49.436 --> 00:12:53.190
No. Elle. stop trying
to help me with anybody.

311
00:12:54.274 --> 00:12:56.610
You don't want
to keep working here. do you?

312
00:12:56.693 --> 00:12:58.028
Of course not.

313
00:12:58.111 --> 00:13:00.197
I hate this place.

314
00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:02.616
A raccoon followed me home last night.

315
00:13:02.699 --> 00:13:03.700
-[man shouts]
-[bell clangs]

316
00:13:03.783 --> 00:13:05.327
But I will be fine.

317
00:13:05.410 --> 00:13:07.370
And you got enough going on
without worrying about me.

318
00:13:07.454 --> 00:13:08.997
so take care of yourself.

319
00:13:09.789 --> 00:13:10.957
Like. seriously.

320
00:13:11.041 --> 00:13:13.001
-Now. Duck. Duck!
-[man] Order! Salmon!

321
00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:19.966
[sighs]

322
00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:22.135
[somber music playing]

323
00:13:28.642 --> 00:13:30.644
[indistinct chatter]

324
00:13:39.778 --> 00:13:40.987
Woods comma Elle?

325
00:13:42.030 --> 00:13:43.907
Hi. I'm Shannon Walker.

326
00:13:43.990 --> 00:13:44.991
Chair of the social committee.

327
00:13:45.951 --> 00:13:48.078
Well. the only member
of the social committee.

328
00:13:48.161 --> 00:13:49.579
Are you okay?

329
00:13:49.663 --> 00:13:52.666
Sorry. I forgot what it was like
to receive eye contact.

330
00:13:52.749 --> 00:13:55.544
[chuckles] Well. I'm here to officially
welcome you to Rainier West High

331
00:13:55.627 --> 00:13:56.878
with this gift basket.

332
00:13:56.962 --> 00:14:00.340
I would have given it to you last week.
but I was in the city visiting FIT.

333
00:14:00.423 --> 00:14:03.093
As in the Fashion Institute of Technology?

334
00:14:03.677 --> 00:14:05.178
Finally someone's heard of it.

335
00:14:06.471 --> 00:14:09.683
I love Seattle. but our style's kind of...
lacking.

336
00:14:09.766 --> 00:14:12.519
Uh. anyway. I'm applying
for early admission.

337
00:14:12.602 --> 00:14:14.104
Being a senior is so stressful.

338
00:14:15.605 --> 00:14:16.731
[whispers] Are you real?

339
00:14:16.815 --> 00:14:18.483
[giggles] You'll find

340
00:14:18.567 --> 00:14:20.193
some super cute spirit wear.

341
00:14:20.277 --> 00:14:21.403
some local beans.

342
00:14:21.486 --> 00:14:23.238
and a book from a Seattle-based author.

343
00:14:23.321 --> 00:14:26.324
I didn't even know
this school had spirit to wear.

344
00:14:26.408 --> 00:14:28.285
I couldn't have curated this
better myself.

345
00:14:28.368 --> 00:14:30.954
Full disclosure:
the Seattle-based author is my mom.

346
00:14:31.037 --> 00:14:32.080
Zero presh to read.

347
00:14:32.163 --> 00:14:34.374
-Anyway. well--
-I got Donna fired.

348
00:14:35.750 --> 00:14:37.419
Oh. my God. I don't know why I said that.

349
00:14:37.502 --> 00:14:39.879
I. I think I'm coming down
with a case of the Marlenas.

350
00:14:39.963 --> 00:14:41.673
I love Days. too!

351
00:14:41.756 --> 00:14:43.508
-Oh. my God. twinsies.
-[chuckles]

352
00:14:43.592 --> 00:14:47.053
But you should have all the facts about me
before you decide how you feel.

353
00:14:47.637 --> 00:14:49.514
I've actually already heard.

354
00:14:49.598 --> 00:14:51.099
Donna was the best. but I don't blame you.

355
00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:53.727
-You don't?
-No. I'm a feminist.

356
00:14:53.810 --> 00:14:56.354
which means I support
women's rights and women's wrongs.

357
00:14:56.438 --> 00:14:58.231
[school bell rings]

358
00:14:58.315 --> 00:15:00.442
Oh. Anyway. got to head.

359
00:15:00.525 --> 00:15:01.943
But the sun's never gone. Elle.

360
00:15:02.027 --> 00:15:03.570
She's just pumping herself up
behind a cloud.

361
00:15:04.821 --> 00:15:05.947
Byes.

362
00:15:06.781 --> 00:15:07.907
Byes.

363
00:15:09.034 --> 00:15:11.036
[optimistic music playing]

364
00:15:14.372 --> 00:15:16.291
Hey. Let me help you with that.

365
00:15:16.374 --> 00:15:17.375
Miles. Hi.

366
00:15:17.459 --> 00:15:18.668
-Hey.
-Thanks.

367
00:15:18.752 --> 00:15:20.337
Yeah.

368
00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:22.130
So you don't hate me either?

369
00:15:23.131 --> 00:15:24.633
Should I hate you?

370
00:15:24.716 --> 00:15:26.259
Preferably not.

371
00:15:26.343 --> 00:15:30.096
Okay. settled.
I will continue not hating you.

372
00:15:32.724 --> 00:15:34.309
Thank you.

373
00:15:34.392 --> 00:15:35.518
Next.

374
00:15:35.602 --> 00:15:37.937
Uh. the vegetarian option. please.

375
00:15:41.232 --> 00:15:42.442
-[chuckles]
-Right.

376
00:15:44.152 --> 00:15:45.403
I know what you're thinking.

377
00:15:45.487 --> 00:15:47.614
Of course the L.A. girl's a vegetarian.

378
00:15:47.697 --> 00:15:51.201
But factory farming's a major contributor
to global warming.

379
00:15:51.284 --> 00:15:52.952
Plus baby cows are really cute.

380
00:15:53.536 --> 00:15:54.579
Agreed.

381
00:15:54.663 --> 00:15:58.166
Uh. unfortunately.
my cross-country coach does not.

382
00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:01.711
My last school didn't have
a cross-country team.

383
00:16:01.795 --> 00:16:03.088
I don't think.

384
00:16:03.171 --> 00:16:05.006
Is that the one where you ski

385
00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:06.299
and then shoot a gun?

386
00:16:06.883 --> 00:16:08.093
Uh...

387
00:16:08.176 --> 00:16:09.969
it-it's running.

388
00:16:10.053 --> 00:16:11.054
You just run.

389
00:16:11.137 --> 00:16:12.263
[chuckles softly]

390
00:16:12.347 --> 00:16:14.557
Well. I don't run.
but I do walk with conviction.

391
00:16:14.641 --> 00:16:16.059
Huh. [chuckles softly]

392
00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:17.560
[chuckles]

393
00:16:20.605 --> 00:16:21.606
What?

394
00:16:22.691 --> 00:16:24.067
Uh. nothing.

395
00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:25.402
Uh...

396
00:16:26.569 --> 00:16:28.571
Hey. are you going
to CarpetMart on Saturday?

397
00:16:28.655 --> 00:16:30.156
Okay. what is CarpetMart?

398
00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:33.034
[stammers] It's not actually about carpet.

399
00:16:33.118 --> 00:16:34.786
Uh. I mean. it is. but it's not.

400
00:16:36.413 --> 00:16:38.498
Okay. that-that really clears things up.

401
00:16:38.581 --> 00:16:39.624
[student] Yo. Miles.

402
00:16:39.708 --> 00:16:40.625
Over here.

403
00:16:41.459 --> 00:16:42.585
Uh...

404
00:16:42.669 --> 00:16:44.754
Anyway. you were saying about Saturday

405
00:16:44.838 --> 00:16:46.798
and inquiring
about my potential availability?

406
00:16:46.881 --> 00:16:48.508
I'm sorry. I...

407
00:16:48.591 --> 00:16:49.592
I got to run.

408
00:16:49.676 --> 00:16:51.845
Uh... do it with conviction.

409
00:16:53.513 --> 00:16:54.514
Enjoy your bun.

410
00:16:54.597 --> 00:16:55.724
I will.

411
00:16:59.436 --> 00:17:01.938
[energetic music playing]

412
00:17:03.022 --> 00:17:04.315
[laughter]

413
00:17:12.073 --> 00:17:13.491
[gasps] Shannon.

414
00:17:13.575 --> 00:17:14.909
[chuckles softly]

415
00:17:14.993 --> 00:17:16.453
-And Kimberly.
-[laughter]

416
00:17:18.413 --> 00:17:19.706
Hey. guys.

417
00:17:19.789 --> 00:17:22.751
[indistinct chatter]

418
00:17:34.763 --> 00:17:37.098
Why. yes. you are
more than welcome to sit here.

419
00:17:37.182 --> 00:17:38.850
-Thanks for asking.
-I don't understand.

420
00:17:38.933 --> 00:17:41.269
Did I misread
Shannon Walker's celestial aura?

421
00:17:41.352 --> 00:17:43.688
I didn't get a gift basket
when I started here.

422
00:17:43.772 --> 00:17:45.231
She's kind. nonjudgmental.

423
00:17:45.315 --> 00:17:46.733
fashion-forward.

424
00:17:46.816 --> 00:17:49.068
She's everything I thought was missing
from this high school.

425
00:17:50.069 --> 00:17:51.613
Thanks?

426
00:17:51.696 --> 00:17:54.407
How could she be friends
with someone like Kimberly?

427
00:17:54.491 --> 00:17:55.492
[all laugh]

428
00:17:55.575 --> 00:17:58.369
Who is obviously relishing
my fall from grace.

429
00:17:59.454 --> 00:18:02.040
I think you're overestimating
how much people liked you before this.

430
00:18:03.124 --> 00:18:06.377
Besides. Kimberly's not mean
around Shannon.

431
00:18:06.461 --> 00:18:08.171
She's the Picasso of being two-faced.

432
00:18:08.254 --> 00:18:11.966
She's also Shannon's guard dog.
so good luck getting past her.

433
00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:13.092
[all laugh]

434
00:18:13.176 --> 00:18:14.761
[sighs]

435
00:18:17.263 --> 00:18:18.681
See. now you're just staring.

436
00:18:19.891 --> 00:18:21.142
Give me my book back.

437
00:18:25.814 --> 00:18:27.065
Hmm.

438
00:18:27.148 --> 00:18:28.817
[Eva] You got this.

439
00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:30.985
Yes. Just look right there.

440
00:18:31.069 --> 00:18:33.905
Right there. Two steps over.

441
00:18:35.448 --> 00:18:36.825
[sighs]

442
00:18:36.908 --> 00:18:38.618
I don't get it. He just stands there.

443
00:18:38.701 --> 00:18:40.537
Come on. Bruiser. [gasps]

444
00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:42.789
Glam-ma modeled this
after the Beverly Wilshire.

445
00:18:42.872 --> 00:18:45.542
It's like you're in Pretty Woman.

446
00:18:45.625 --> 00:18:46.960
-Except you kiss on the lips.
-[Bruiser whines]

447
00:18:47.043 --> 00:18:47.961
[kissing]

448
00:18:48.044 --> 00:18:49.504
[chuckles]

449
00:18:49.587 --> 00:18:50.755
Oh.

450
00:18:50.839 --> 00:18:54.092
The upstairs guest room
with the warmer daylight.

451
00:18:54.175 --> 00:18:55.426
Thank you.

452
00:18:56.052 --> 00:19:00.473
Wait. are you refurnishing
the entire house?

453
00:19:00.557 --> 00:19:04.561
Well. at first I resisted
because it felt so permanent.

454
00:19:04.644 --> 00:19:07.063
But isn't it already feeling more us?

455
00:19:08.147 --> 00:19:09.440
And get this.

456
00:19:09.524 --> 00:19:12.402
As I was power walking.
I spotted a fabulous gay couple

457
00:19:12.485 --> 00:19:15.780
driving a Corvette
and a woman walking a border collie.

458
00:19:15.864 --> 00:19:17.866
-And you know what that means.
-What?

459
00:19:17.949 --> 00:19:20.910
Our neighborhood
is the perfect combination

460
00:19:20.994 --> 00:19:23.371
of socially liberal
and fiscally conservative.

461
00:19:23.454 --> 00:19:25.582
So we basically moved to cloudy Brentwood.

462
00:19:25.665 --> 00:19:27.000
Yeah.

463
00:19:27.876 --> 00:19:30.253
I'm thinking of hosting
a little housewarming party

464
00:19:30.336 --> 00:19:31.796
to get to know the community.

465
00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:34.007
Speaking of community-building.

466
00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:37.677
my classmate's mom wrote a book
and she's having an event tonight.

467
00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:39.554
-Oh. wow.
-Yeah.

468
00:19:39.637 --> 00:19:42.015
Shannon's the first person
I've connected with here.

469
00:19:42.098 --> 00:19:44.517
She basically radiates positivity.

470
00:19:44.601 --> 00:19:47.562
And you've always told me optimism.

471
00:19:47.645 --> 00:19:49.063
like bone structure.

472
00:19:49.147 --> 00:19:50.356
-is genetic.
-Is genetic.

473
00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:52.483
-We should go.
-Oh.

474
00:19:53.818 --> 00:19:55.194
I don't know. Elle.

475
00:19:55.278 --> 00:19:58.406
I don't love the color story
of that book cover.

476
00:19:59.616 --> 00:20:01.034
But...

477
00:20:01.117 --> 00:20:03.995
you know who likes to go to book readings?

478
00:20:04.078 --> 00:20:06.039
People who can't afford TVs?

479
00:20:06.122 --> 00:20:09.417
People who like being invited...
[singsongy] to housewarmings.

480
00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:10.501
[chuckles]

481
00:20:10.585 --> 00:20:12.337
[Robin] "And then it hit me.

482
00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.923
I couldn't run from my past.

483
00:20:15.006 --> 00:20:16.007
Instead.

484
00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:18.968
like the mountains before me.
I had to traverse it.

485
00:20:19.052 --> 00:20:20.720
Because sometimes the route to the top

486
00:20:20.803 --> 00:20:22.847
isn't the most direct.

487
00:20:22.931 --> 00:20:25.558
It zigs and it zags.

488
00:20:25.642 --> 00:20:28.102
but the struggle made me who I am."

489
00:20:30.146 --> 00:20:31.147
Thank you.

490
00:20:35.526 --> 00:20:36.861
She has such a way with words.

491
00:20:36.945 --> 00:20:38.363
Very evocative.

492
00:20:38.446 --> 00:20:41.157
I felt like I was being wrongfully evicted

493
00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:43.117
-right alongside her.
-Yes.

494
00:20:43.201 --> 00:20:45.453
Wow. Let's go get our copies.

495
00:20:48.414 --> 00:20:49.832
So nice to meet you. Sierra.

496
00:20:49.916 --> 00:20:51.250
-You. too.
-[champagne cork pops]

497
00:20:51.334 --> 00:20:53.127
And there's bubbles?

498
00:20:53.211 --> 00:20:55.755
Elle. we should really
have books read to us more often.

499
00:20:55.838 --> 00:20:57.548
-I know.
-[Shannon] Elle.

500
00:20:57.632 --> 00:20:58.675
-Shannon. Hi.
-Come here.

501
00:20:58.758 --> 00:21:00.218
Hi. Oh.

502
00:21:00.969 --> 00:21:01.970
That was amazing.

503
00:21:02.053 --> 00:21:05.139
Your mom rocks.
And climbs them. too. apparently.

504
00:21:05.223 --> 00:21:06.557
I can't believe you came.

505
00:21:06.641 --> 00:21:09.185
Nobody at school
ever comes to these kinds of things.

506
00:21:09.268 --> 00:21:11.813
I mean. it's a book reading.
not CarpetMart. but still.

507
00:21:11.896 --> 00:21:13.815
Are you going tomorrow?

508
00:21:13.898 --> 00:21:15.191
Totally.

509
00:21:15.274 --> 00:21:16.985
I definitely know what that is.

510
00:21:18.152 --> 00:21:19.320
I love carpet.

511
00:21:19.404 --> 00:21:21.698
I always thought rugs were phoning it in.

512
00:21:21.781 --> 00:21:23.408
[laughs] Elle. you're so funny.

513
00:21:23.491 --> 00:21:24.867
-And so stylish.
-Aw.

514
00:21:24.951 --> 00:21:25.910
I wouldn't wear

515
00:21:25.994 --> 00:21:26.995
those cute suede boots outside. though.

516
00:21:27.078 --> 00:21:28.204
Oh. these are Ultrasuede.

517
00:21:28.287 --> 00:21:31.541
Faux suede that is animal-
and cruelty-free. And waterproof.

518
00:21:31.624 --> 00:21:33.126
Oh. thank God.
Because Seattle women don't wear suede.

519
00:21:33.209 --> 00:21:35.044
Everyone knows you can't wear soft leather

520
00:21:35.128 --> 00:21:37.505
in a city that rains 160 days a year.

521
00:21:37.588 --> 00:21:40.800
Even I know that.
I'm not even from... Seattle.

522
00:21:40.883 --> 00:21:42.301
[gasps]

523
00:21:42.385 --> 00:21:44.637
Principal Anderson's having an affair.

524
00:21:44.721 --> 00:21:46.681
This way. this way.

525
00:21:47.932 --> 00:21:50.351
Oh. my God. Ew. How do you know this?

526
00:21:50.435 --> 00:21:52.979
So. yesterday I was in his office
and I commented on

527
00:21:53.062 --> 00:21:55.773
an orange suede jacket
he claimed was his wife's.

528
00:21:55.857 --> 00:21:59.444
And I thought. "That's a bad color match
for a redhead. but who am I to judge?"

529
00:21:59.527 --> 00:22:01.988
And then he said
she had gone to every Mariners game

530
00:22:02.071 --> 00:22:05.450
since she was a toddler. which means
she was born and raised in Seattle. and...

531
00:22:05.533 --> 00:22:07.201
-Seattle women don't wear suede.
-Seattle women don't wear suede.

532
00:22:07.285 --> 00:22:08.870
The jacket must belong
to some other woman.

533
00:22:08.953 --> 00:22:10.329
-Why else would he lie?
-Mm-hmm. Exactly.

534
00:22:10.413 --> 00:22:11.497
Oh. this is perfect.

535
00:22:11.581 --> 00:22:14.500
I can use this as leverage to get
Donna out of that job that she hates.

536
00:22:14.584 --> 00:22:16.419
[chuckles] Oh. my God.
I love the way you talk.

537
00:22:16.502 --> 00:22:17.503
You have to let me help.

538
00:22:17.587 --> 00:22:19.464
Seriously? It won't be easy. though.

539
00:22:19.547 --> 00:22:21.090
To be honest...

540
00:22:21.174 --> 00:22:24.052
I've never used
the word "leverage" before in my life.

541
00:22:24.135 --> 00:22:26.429
Marlena and John
went up against a literal demon.

542
00:22:26.512 --> 00:22:28.139
How hard could it be
to get Donna's job back?

543
00:22:28.222 --> 00:22:29.265
True. Ah. you're so smart.

544
00:22:29.348 --> 00:22:30.266
[both laugh]

545
00:22:30.349 --> 00:22:33.519
"Live. laugh. love."

546
00:22:33.603 --> 00:22:35.897
Oh. That's profound.

547
00:22:35.980 --> 00:22:39.025
-Thank you.
-And speaking of profound.

548
00:22:39.108 --> 00:22:41.110
this is my Elle.

549
00:22:41.194 --> 00:22:42.570
Oh.

550
00:22:42.653 --> 00:22:43.654
-[Elle] Hi.
-It is so nice

551
00:22:43.738 --> 00:22:44.989
of you both to come.

552
00:22:45.073 --> 00:22:46.491
L.A. women are so friendly.

553
00:22:46.574 --> 00:22:49.452
You and Shannon must
come over for drinks sometime.

554
00:22:49.535 --> 00:22:51.746
I make a killer cocktail. And mocktail.

555
00:22:51.829 --> 00:22:52.914
Oh. it's true.

556
00:22:52.997 --> 00:22:55.875
Her Heavy Petting on the Beach
is to die for.

557
00:22:55.958 --> 00:22:57.376
We would love that.

558
00:22:57.460 --> 00:22:59.003
Oh. mind if we head out?

559
00:22:59.087 --> 00:23:01.422
I need your advice
on how to handle a juicy piece of intel.

560
00:23:01.506 --> 00:23:02.465
Sure.

561
00:23:02.548 --> 00:23:05.009
I just wanted to tell Robin.

562
00:23:05.093 --> 00:23:07.261
your book reminded me so much

563
00:23:07.345 --> 00:23:09.013
of my husband's botched nose job.

564
00:23:10.515 --> 00:23:12.517
My book on systemic discrimination?

565
00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:13.893
I'm sure you read about it.

566
00:23:13.976 --> 00:23:15.853
The coverage was awful. The Post headline

567
00:23:15.937 --> 00:23:18.397
was clever. but the article itself

568
00:23:18.481 --> 00:23:21.192
lacked all journalistic integrity.

569
00:23:21.275 --> 00:23:22.777
Anyway. there we were.

570
00:23:22.860 --> 00:23:25.321
at rock bottom. faced with a choice.

571
00:23:25.404 --> 00:23:27.824
We could crawl into a hole and die.

572
00:23:27.907 --> 00:23:29.158
or...

573
00:23:29.242 --> 00:23:30.785
we could zig and zag

574
00:23:30.868 --> 00:23:33.329
our way to a new city

575
00:23:33.412 --> 00:23:36.207
with a fresh start. and here we are.

576
00:23:37.875 --> 00:23:39.252
Surviving.

577
00:23:40.753 --> 00:23:42.964
That sounds harrowing.

578
00:23:43.047 --> 00:23:45.007
Robin. it was.

579
00:23:45.091 --> 00:23:47.969
Hmm. Well. I'm glad
you enjoyed the book. Eva.

580
00:23:48.052 --> 00:23:49.303
I loved it.

581
00:23:49.387 --> 00:23:50.429
-[man clears throat]
-[Eva chuckles]

582
00:23:50.513 --> 00:23:53.432
Mom. there's-there's
a line forming behind us.

583
00:23:53.516 --> 00:23:54.725
Thanks.

584
00:23:54.809 --> 00:23:56.310
-Bye. ladies.
-Bye.

585
00:23:56.394 --> 00:23:57.770
-[Elle] Bye.
-Byes.

586
00:24:00.273 --> 00:24:02.900
-[door opens]
-[entry bell jingles]

587
00:24:07.113 --> 00:24:08.364
[Elle groaning]

588
00:24:08.447 --> 00:24:09.615
-[knock on door]
-[Wyatt] Hey.

589
00:24:09.699 --> 00:24:11.492
I want to suffocate myself.

590
00:24:11.576 --> 00:24:13.578
Oh. I mean. the book was rough.

591
00:24:13.661 --> 00:24:15.955
but that last third was so uplifting.

592
00:24:16.038 --> 00:24:17.206
[sighs]

593
00:24:18.332 --> 00:24:21.878
Mom compared your botched surgery
to Robin getting kicked out of her house.

594
00:24:21.961 --> 00:24:23.212
Ah.

595
00:24:24.922 --> 00:24:27.133
Well. in her defense.
I don't think your mom's known

596
00:24:27.216 --> 00:24:30.303
many activists turned adventurers
turned spoken-word artists.

597
00:24:30.386 --> 00:24:33.347
Wow. You really did read the book.

598
00:24:33.431 --> 00:24:35.266
Again. a lot of free time here.

599
00:24:35.349 --> 00:24:38.227
I love Mom.
but I wish I brought you instead.

600
00:24:39.812 --> 00:24:42.440
So embarrassing.

601
00:24:42.523 --> 00:24:44.442
I mean. everyone already thinks

602
00:24:44.525 --> 00:24:46.819
I'm the self-centered L.A. girl. and now

603
00:24:46.903 --> 00:24:49.363
the one person who was open
to getting to know me thinks it. too.

604
00:24:49.447 --> 00:24:52.533
Well. it's not the first time
your mom's over-involved herself.

605
00:24:53.743 --> 00:24:55.745
I think she's just looking
to connect with people.

606
00:24:55.828 --> 00:24:57.246
[Elle] Yeah. well. it's hereditary.

607
00:24:57.330 --> 00:24:59.123
And not in the "good cheekbones" way.

608
00:25:00.791 --> 00:25:02.752
If I hadn't over-involved myself

609
00:25:02.835 --> 00:25:06.172
by trying to connect
with people in that school auction.

610
00:25:06.255 --> 00:25:08.049
I wouldn't be in this situation.

611
00:25:08.132 --> 00:25:10.301
Perhaps. but maybe
there's some good news for you

612
00:25:10.384 --> 00:25:12.803
about this terrible hereditary condition.

613
00:25:12.887 --> 00:25:13.804
Doubtful.

614
00:25:13.888 --> 00:25:16.349
Your mom never stays down for long.

615
00:25:16.432 --> 00:25:19.602
and she has more friends
than anyone I've ever met.

616
00:25:19.685 --> 00:25:21.646
And so do you.

617
00:25:21.729 --> 00:25:22.939
Yeah.

618
00:25:25.441 --> 00:25:28.903
Actually. I need your help with something.

619
00:25:37.328 --> 00:25:39.163
[♪ X-Ray Spex plays "I Am a Poseur"]

620
00:25:44.669 --> 00:25:46.170
-[door opens]
-[entry bell jingles]

621
00:25:54.512 --> 00:25:56.138
Hi.

622
00:25:56.222 --> 00:25:57.807
Okay. are you stalking me?

623
00:25:57.890 --> 00:25:59.100
'Cause this is starting
to feel like stalking.

624
00:25:59.183 --> 00:26:01.018
You don't exactly make it hard to find you

625
00:26:01.102 --> 00:26:04.355
when the only clothing you own is
Bad Vibrations paraphernalia.

626
00:26:04.438 --> 00:26:07.316
That's called victim-blaming.
and it's not the only clothing I own.

627
00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:09.318
♪ Voyeurism is the game ♪

628
00:26:09.402 --> 00:26:10.319
♪ Stereoscopic...

629
00:26:10.403 --> 00:26:11.821
Whatever.

630
00:26:11.904 --> 00:26:14.448
♪ Viewing time makes it grow...

631
00:26:14.532 --> 00:26:16.951
Is this you?
I didn't know you were a musician.

632
00:26:17.034 --> 00:26:18.202
-[Todd] She's not.
-Shut up. Todd.

633
00:26:18.286 --> 00:26:19.578
She's only sold one copy.

634
00:26:19.662 --> 00:26:20.997
Please shut up. Todd.

635
00:26:22.123 --> 00:26:24.709
I sing. Sometimes.

636
00:26:24.792 --> 00:26:27.003
My mom says
it looks good on a college application.

637
00:26:27.086 --> 00:26:29.213
What are your top choices?

638
00:26:29.297 --> 00:26:30.923
Oberlin?

639
00:26:31.007 --> 00:26:32.008
Juilliard?

640
00:26:33.718 --> 00:26:34.802
Berklee with an "E"?

641
00:26:34.885 --> 00:26:36.887
Uh. Seattle Community College?

642
00:26:36.971 --> 00:26:38.472
[gasps] That's great.

643
00:26:38.556 --> 00:26:40.766
You know. Teri Hatcher
went to community college.

644
00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:42.143
Okay. why are you here?

645
00:26:42.226 --> 00:26:45.229
Um. so I actually found out

646
00:26:45.313 --> 00:26:47.898
that CarpetMart is a carpet store

647
00:26:47.982 --> 00:26:50.693
that inexplicably turns
into a music venue at night.

648
00:26:50.776 --> 00:26:53.696
The carpets help with acoustics.
Obviously.

649
00:26:53.779 --> 00:26:56.449
Because the idea of using a venue

650
00:26:56.532 --> 00:26:59.327
originally designed for music
is a poser move. [gasps]

651
00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:00.619
See? I'm getting this.

652
00:27:02.705 --> 00:27:04.332
Anyway. I thought maybe
we could go together.

653
00:27:07.877 --> 00:27:10.212
Okay. um... [clears throat]

654
00:27:10.296 --> 00:27:11.964
So. tonight is the kickoff show

655
00:27:12.048 --> 00:27:14.884
for Bob's Your Uncle's
Pacific Northwest tour.

656
00:27:14.967 --> 00:27:17.136
They're like the next big thing
in grunge. It's totally sold out.

657
00:27:17.219 --> 00:27:20.556
Oh. nothing's ever really sold out.

658
00:27:21.557 --> 00:27:22.975
Seriously.

659
00:27:23.059 --> 00:27:26.479
I asked my dad to get us tickets.
He can do anything.

660
00:27:27.563 --> 00:27:30.232
300 square feet of cut-and-loop Berber.

661
00:27:30.316 --> 00:27:33.361
and that is my final offer. Hello? Hello?

662
00:27:33.444 --> 00:27:34.737
[recorded message] If you'd
like to make a call...

663
00:27:34.820 --> 00:27:36.197
Honey?

664
00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:38.115
Our floors are perfect now.

665
00:27:38.199 --> 00:27:40.201
My rug guy took us
on that full texture journey.

666
00:27:40.284 --> 00:27:41.118
I remember.

667
00:27:41.202 --> 00:27:44.080
and I agree. it looks great.
I'm on a different mission.

668
00:27:44.163 --> 00:27:45.289
Elle's asked me to help her

669
00:27:45.373 --> 00:27:47.541
get into some sold-out concert.

670
00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:51.837
Elle asked you to get her tickets?

671
00:27:51.921 --> 00:27:53.255
She probably saw how busy you were

672
00:27:53.339 --> 00:27:55.049
with the house
and didn't want to bother you.

673
00:27:56.050 --> 00:27:57.218
You're being sweet.

674
00:27:58.511 --> 00:27:59.887
I embarrassed her.

675
00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:01.639
Well.

676
00:28:01.722 --> 00:28:05.393
all I got her was a VIP pass
to a carpet convention in Tukwila.

677
00:28:07.645 --> 00:28:08.646
Okay.

678
00:28:09.647 --> 00:28:12.942
For music-related inquiries.
including tickets and events.

679
00:28:13.025 --> 00:28:14.777
we call Simon LeDoux.

680
00:28:14.860 --> 00:28:16.153
Got it. Simon LeDoux.

681
00:28:18.864 --> 00:28:20.741
-Madison's dad.
-Mm-hmm.

682
00:28:21.909 --> 00:28:23.911
He's produced more albums than Rick Rubin.

683
00:28:24.703 --> 00:28:26.497
I may have been a little
checked out back at home.

684
00:28:26.580 --> 00:28:28.457
-huh?
-A little.

685
00:28:30.167 --> 00:28:32.128
Please bring me my Rolodex

686
00:28:32.211 --> 00:28:34.672
and a dry martini.

687
00:28:34.755 --> 00:28:36.632
Thank you. [clears throat]

688
00:28:42.263 --> 00:28:43.556
[bouncer] Next.

689
00:28:43.639 --> 00:28:46.392
So. just to be clear. once we're inside.
I will be ditching you.

690
00:28:46.475 --> 00:28:47.768
Oh. Okay.

691
00:28:47.852 --> 00:28:49.687
Well. I appreciate your cut-to-itiveness.

692
00:28:49.770 --> 00:28:53.274
I'll just huddle with Shannon and
figure out how to get Donna her job back.

693
00:28:53.357 --> 00:28:55.025
[bouncer] Next.

694
00:28:55.109 --> 00:28:57.278
-[♪ The Halo Benders play
"Don't Touch My Bikini"]
-♪ Heavy breathing. hunting season ♪

695
00:28:57.361 --> 00:29:00.072
♪ There's no reason we can't form a plan ♪

696
00:29:00.156 --> 00:29:03.659
♪ Don't touch my graffiti ♪

697
00:29:03.742 --> 00:29:06.036
♪ Smile if you dare. oily oinkers...

698
00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:07.288
A trust system.

699
00:29:08.289 --> 00:29:10.458
I'm sure this is fine.

700
00:29:10.541 --> 00:29:11.750
[Liz] Uh. I thought Donna asked you

701
00:29:11.834 --> 00:29:13.419
to stop pestering Anderson.

702
00:29:13.502 --> 00:29:15.880
Oh. she was just looking out for me.

703
00:29:15.963 --> 00:29:18.424
But once she sees
the terrifying blackmail note

704
00:29:18.507 --> 00:29:21.510
I crafted using letters from
old Us Weeklies. she's gonna...

705
00:29:21.594 --> 00:29:24.180
Wait. how'd you know Donna
asked me to stop pestering Anderson?

706
00:29:25.848 --> 00:29:27.600
Shannon. hi.

707
00:29:27.683 --> 00:29:29.101
Oh. I can't talk.
Boyfriend's at will call.

708
00:29:29.185 --> 00:29:30.019
Oh.

709
00:29:30.811 --> 00:29:32.021
[Kimberly] What's up. Pink Slip?

710
00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:36.233
Why are you here with the chick
who got your mom fired?

711
00:29:38.486 --> 00:29:39.445
Wait. what?

712
00:29:39.528 --> 00:29:40.821
I'm not.

713
00:29:43.824 --> 00:29:44.950
What's wrong. Elle? You look like

714
00:29:45.034 --> 00:29:46.535
you've seen a chipped manicure.

715
00:29:46.619 --> 00:29:47.953
[chuckles] Burn.

716
00:29:49.038 --> 00:29:50.331
Liz?

717
00:29:52.458 --> 00:29:54.960
Excuse me. sorry. Liz?

718
00:29:55.044 --> 00:29:56.128
Liz?

719
00:29:57.129 --> 00:29:58.130
Hang on.

720
00:29:58.214 --> 00:30:00.508
Hey. s-since when is Donna your mom?

721
00:30:00.591 --> 00:30:01.717
Since birth.

722
00:30:02.301 --> 00:30:03.761
Why didn't you tell me?

723
00:30:03.844 --> 00:30:05.387
Because you never asked.

724
00:30:05.471 --> 00:30:06.931
Well. that's not fair.

725
00:30:07.014 --> 00:30:09.183
I haven't asked anyone
who their parents are in Seattle.

726
00:30:09.266 --> 00:30:11.393
In L.A.. I only know 'cause of E! News.

727
00:30:11.477 --> 00:30:13.646
We live out of district. okay?

728
00:30:13.729 --> 00:30:15.814
My mom just told me
that me going to our school

729
00:30:15.898 --> 00:30:19.527
hinges on her working there. which means
I should have gotten kicked out

730
00:30:19.610 --> 00:30:21.820
when she did. but Anderson was willing

731
00:30:21.904 --> 00:30:24.573
to fudge the paperwork
to keep me enrolled.

732
00:30:24.657 --> 00:30:25.574
He can. he can do that?

733
00:30:25.658 --> 00:30:26.784
He did do that.

734
00:30:26.867 --> 00:30:28.536
So if you start accusing him

735
00:30:28.619 --> 00:30:31.747
of cheating via what I assume
is a sparkly pink ransom note

736
00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:33.999
on my mom's behalf.
I'm pretty sure I'd get kicked out. too.

737
00:30:34.750 --> 00:30:36.669
I-I don't want you to get kicked out.

738
00:30:36.752 --> 00:30:38.254
Then please. just...

739
00:30:38.337 --> 00:30:39.547
give up.

740
00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:41.048
[feedback whines]

741
00:30:41.131 --> 00:30:42.841
[♪ "All Ages Show"]

742
00:30:42.925 --> 00:30:44.802
[crowd cheering]

743
00:30:55.813 --> 00:30:59.191
♪ Knee-highs to the sky ♪

744
00:30:59.275 --> 00:31:03.737
♪ Gliding down the street
with the sun in her eye-eye-eyes ♪

745
00:31:03.821 --> 00:31:05.656
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

746
00:31:05.739 --> 00:31:09.493
-♪ Eye-eye-eye-eyes ♪
-♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

747
00:31:09.577 --> 00:31:11.787
♪ Eye-eye-eye-eyes...

748
00:31:13.914 --> 00:31:15.457
You look like you're having fun.

749
00:31:16.834 --> 00:31:19.461
Everything just feels backwards here.

750
00:31:20.337 --> 00:31:22.756
You are from a city
that pays TV doctors more than real ones.

751
00:31:23.716 --> 00:31:28.053
I mean. I try to be charitable.
but I just get people fired.

752
00:31:28.137 --> 00:31:30.973
I try to get Donna her job back.
but that's just making things worse.

753
00:31:31.056 --> 00:31:33.225
But Principal Anderson fudges paperwork

754
00:31:33.309 --> 00:31:34.768
and cheats on his wife.
and he's a freaking hero.

755
00:31:34.852 --> 00:31:36.687
Wait. what do you mean. fudges paperwork?

756
00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:38.772
[sighs] I don't know.
I didn't exactly catch the details

757
00:31:38.856 --> 00:31:40.190
amidst my existential crisis.

758
00:31:40.274 --> 00:31:41.609
But he's doing something shady?

759
00:31:41.692 --> 00:31:42.901
-[sighs]
-'Cause I always thought there was

760
00:31:42.985 --> 00:31:44.486
something deeper going on
with the underpaid support staff--

761
00:31:44.570 --> 00:31:45.863
I want to give up!

762
00:31:50.409 --> 00:31:51.952
I've never said that before.

763
00:31:52.786 --> 00:31:55.205
Those words have never entered my mind.

764
00:31:56.248 --> 00:31:57.166
What?

765
00:31:57.249 --> 00:31:58.834
No. No. this place

766
00:31:58.917 --> 00:32:00.252
will not change me.

767
00:32:00.336 --> 00:32:03.547
Cosmo girls are down but not out.

768
00:32:03.631 --> 00:32:05.466
Elle Woods doesn't give up.

769
00:32:06.967 --> 00:32:08.427
She doesn't.

770
00:32:09.303 --> 00:32:10.220
Okay.

771
00:32:10.304 --> 00:32:11.847
What-what are you doing?

772
00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:13.182
Getting you out of your head.

773
00:32:13.265 --> 00:32:14.475
I'm in wedges!

774
00:32:17.102 --> 00:32:18.604
